Prosperity or Decline? Post-communist Transformations Revisited

More than three decades after the collapse of communism in Middle and Eastern Europe, there is an ongoing political instability in the region which now dramatically manifests itself in the Russian invasion to Ukraine. Debates are intensifying on how to evaluate the process and the outcomes of the post-communist transformations.   

One of the earliest contributions to this debate is the book Taking Stock of Shock: Social Consequences of the 1989 Revolutions, which has drawn wide attention even in the Czech Republic, notably in the newspaper Salon Pr√°va.

Together with its authors Kristen Ghodsee and Mitchell Orenstein, US-American researchers, we are going to discuss why the latest development in the post-communist space can be labeled prosperity and decline at the same time and what are the political consequences of it for today.

My house is my fortress

How can people in Ukraine be helped, what contribution can one personally make? These are currently two of many questions that many people are likely asking since the Russian attack on Ukraine on February 24, which abruptly ended a period of peace in Europe. The news and pictures that have reached us from Ukraine since then are difficult to bear. The suffering that befalls the Ukrainian civilian population is hard to imagine. It is all the more important to maintain contact with the people in Ukraine and to show solidarity with them and the Ukraine.

Together with the Organization for the Help of Refugees (OPU) and the Democratic Masaryk Academy (MDA), the Prague office of the FES is therefore organizing on March 24th. at 7 p.m. a vernissage in the FES Arena to present works by the Ukrainian Instagramer Iryna Vale and thus offer her a stage.

The following will speak about the artist's work:

Urban √úbersch√§r, head of the Friedrich Ebert Foundation in Prague

Martin Rozumek, Head of OPU

Vladim√≠r ≈†pidla, Head of MDA

The vernissage is also expressly intended as a call for donations to support the work of the organization that helps refugees. Everyone, of course, according to his or her possibilities. Every contribution helps and gets where it is needed!
https://www.opu.cz/en/

-------------------------------------------
Iryna Vale is an illustrator based in Kyiv. She specializes in sketching and collages. In peacetime, she used to teach sketching, wrote a column about illustrations specialized edition. Now she draws as a volunteer for several projects that donate proceeds to the Ukrainian army.

Access to the virtual vernissage on Zoom:
https://us02web.zoom.us/j/88120819887

The vernissage will be interpreted from English into Czech.
